  "prompt": "How water is supplied automatically for embedded green house automation system?",
  "response": "In an embedded greenhouse automation system, water can be supplied automatically through several methods:\n\n1. Soil Moisture Sensor-Based Irrigation\n- Soil moisture sensors detect current moisture levels\n- When moisture drops below a preset threshold, automatic watering is triggered\n- Ensures precise and efficient water management\n\n2. Drip Irrigation System\n- Uses programmable valves and drip lines\n- Water is delivered directly to plant roots\n- Controlled by microcontrollers and sensors\n- Minimizes water wastage\n\n3. Automated Water Pump Control\n- Water pump activated based on predefined conditions\n- Triggered by moisture sensors or timer settings\n- Connected to water reservoir or main water supply\n\n4. Components and Technologies\n- Microcontroller (Arduino/Raspberry Pi)\n- Soil moisture sensors\n- Water flow sensors\n- Solenoid valves\n- Water pumps\n- Irrigation pipes/drip lines\n\n5. Additional Features\n- Real-time monitoring\n- Remote control via mobile/web applications\n- Data logging of irrigation cycles\n- Integration with environmental sensors\n\n6. Water Source Options\n- Underground water tank\n- Municipal water supply\n- Rainwater harvesting system\n\nThe system ensures optimal water supply with minimal human intervention.",
